sec.p:
In this work we establish that oxygen vacancies (VO’s) in the Dirac nodal line (DNL) materials IrO2 and RuO2 drive an orbital Kondo effect. VO’s are prevalent in transition-metal oxides, including, e.g., TiO2 and SrTiO3, and their properties and ramifications have become central research topics as they can lead to an intricate entanglement of spin, orbital, and charge degrees of freedom12–15. The active degree of freedom in the orbital Kondo effect is not a local spin moment but a ‘pseudospin’ formed by orbital degrees of freedom4. In IrO2 and RuO2, the orbital Kondo effect is symmetry stabilized by the space-group symmetries of the rutile structure (Fig. 1). Both materials have been characterized as topological metals which feature symmetry-protected DNLs in their Brillouin zones16,17. This provides a link between the formation of the orbital Kondo effect and the presence of DNLs. In IrO2 a nonmagnetic 2CK ground state ensues, while in RuO2 the absence of time-reversal symmetry results in an orbital one-channel Kondo (1CK) effect.Fig. 1Atomic arrangement around an oxygen vacancy in MO2 rutile structure.
